#: ../../source/creating_movements.rst:259
msgid "Using Hooks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/creating_movements.rst:260
msgid ""
"Hooks are reference points that can be defined for any animation level "
"directly in the viewer, by using the **Hook** tool (|hook|)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/creating_movements.rst:262
msgid ""
"Once defined for a column/layer, they can be used in the Stage Schematic "
"to link another object to it in relation to a specific hook, or to move "
"it, according to any of its hook sets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/creating_movements.rst:264
msgid ""
"In the first case the hook is used as a tracking point to link another "
"object (a column/layer or camera) to a specific feature of the animation "
"level. For example, if you have a character carrying a lamp, you can "
"track the lamp position with a hook, and link a radial gradient to it "
"(placed over the lamp for every frame of the animation) to create a glow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/creating_movements.rst:266
msgid ""
"In the second case, the hook is used as the center of the column/layer "
"where the hooked level will be exposed, thus creating a different center "
"and offset for each level frame. For example, if you have a walking "
"animation cycle, you can set a new center following the character’s feet "
"with a hook, and make the level move accordingly to prevent a moon-"
"walking effect on the background."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/creating_movements.rst:268
msgid ""
"Hooks can also be split and passed from one drawing feature to another, "
"automatically creating an offset position. For example, the hook "
"following the character’s foot feature can pass from one foot to another,"
" in order to make the character move continuously onward."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/creating_movements.rst:273
msgid ""
"The hook set 2 follows the lamp, while the hook set 1 follows the "
"character’s feet, passing from one feet to another when both are on the "
"ground."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/creating_movements.rst:276
msgid ""
"A hook can be created starting from any frame. Once it is created, it "
"will appear on the following level frames in the same position, from "
"where it can be moved."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/creating_movements.rst:278
msgid ""
"You can use up to 20 hooks for each level; each hook is labeled with a "
"number, to reference it in each level frame."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/creating_movements.rst:280
msgid ""
"By activating the **Snap** option, hooks for the current level can be "
"accurately placed by snapping them exactly to the same position of hooks "
"defined for the other animation levels visible in the viewer. In case the"
" current level is a Toonz Vector level, hooks will snap also to the "
"center of any closed shapes it may contain (e.g. rectangles, circles or "
"single vector shapes closed with the Tape tool). This option may prove "
"useful especially when defining hooks for cutout animation models (see  "
":ref:`Creating Cutout Animation <creating_cutout_animation>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/creating_movements.rst:282
msgid ""
"Hook information is saved along with each level, as a file in XML format,"
" named as the file but with the *_hooks* suffix. For example, hooks "
"defined for the level ``mouse``  will be saved in the file "
"``mouse_hooks.xml`` ."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/creating_movements.rst:284
msgid ""
"Hooks are also visible in Onion Skin mode (see  :ref:`Using Onion Skin "
"<using_onion_skin>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/creating_movements.rst:286
